<br>
Please recognize that there's room for reasonable people to disagree on this issue.<br>
<br>
While earlier I was stating the reality of the situation, I also prefer things to be one character, and I've been on the server, causing one ruckus or another, since the first week (started on day one, but went back to SZ for a week when I couldn't get a kill in edgewise due to the rampant KSing of orc pawns, bees, spiders, etc).  I'm not some &quot;newb&quot; who showed up 4-6 months later.<br>
<br>
However, I understand why people want alternates.  There are times I'd really like to reprise my AD&amp;D paladin Sarah, and FV would be the perfect place for her.<br>
<br>
I think Verant screwed up from the get-go by a) having so many servers and then b) also allowing 8 characters per server except on FV and SZ.  But what's done is done, and there's no use complaining about it now.<br>
<br>
I had 40 characters in my partner's AD&amp;D campaign, at last count, but he had a meta-rule in his campaign that forbade characters of the same player to meet one another--and a harsh rule, at that.  If they did, he (the DM) absorbed one of them as an NPC under his control--permanently.  Coupled with the fact that each magic item that wasn't a limited-charge item (wands, potions, etc) was unique (meaning only one Short Sword +1, one Holy Avenger, etc.), and what we know as &quot;twinking&quot; was just impossible.  Finding a magic item, any magic item, was an Event, capital &quot;E&quot;, no matter how piddly the item actually was.  Anyway, I guess I'm trying to say I understand the urge to create multiple characters and explore what they can do.  I've done it myself in other RPG settings, and there were times I just did not want to play my evil necromancer, and other times I didn't want to play her twin. <p><center><img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~andersonrob/lasgalensig.jpg" border="0"></center>
